<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="246" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,493,707]" pageId="3" pageNumber="246">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,306,493,522]" pageId="3" pageNumber="246">Diagnosis –</emphasis>
Venilia-type striation (
<bibRefCitation author="Kazmierski, A." box="[603,829,494,523]" pageId="3" pageNumber="246" pagination="283 - 455" refId="ref3898" refString="Kazmierski, A. (1998) Tydeinae of the world: generic relationships, new and redescribed taxa and keys to all species. A revision of the subfamilies Pretydeinae and Tydeinae (Acari: Actinedida: Tydeidae) - part IV. Acta Zoologica Cracoviensia, 41: 283 - 455." type="journal article" year="1998">Kaźmierski 1998</bibRefCitation>
). Eupathidia of palps cleft distally; gnathosoma protrudes from anterior part of aspidosoma, with only its base concealed (
<figureCitation box="[1097,1175,530,560]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="3.[151,227,1950,1974]" captionTargetBox="[153,1432,1075,1928]" captionTargetId="graphics-195@3.[153,794,1075,1928]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figure 2. Habitus of Lorryia maga female, dorsal view (left) and dorsal idiosomal setae and striations (right)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4644998" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4644998/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="246">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,493,707]" pageId="3" pageNumber="246">
This species was first described as 
<taxonomicName authority="(Kuznetzov, 1973)" baseAuthorityName="Kuznetzov" baseAuthorityYear="1973" box="[610,1040,567,596]" genus="Venilia" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="3" pageNumber="246" rank="species" species="maga">
<emphasis box="[610,784,567,596]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="246">Venilia maga</emphasis>
(Kuznetzov, 1973)
</taxonomicName>
. This is the first record of this species from 
<collectingRegion box="[322,600,604,633]" country="Iran" name="Mazandaran" pageId="3" pageNumber="246">Mazandaran province</collectingRegion>
and the first photograph of its dorsum.
</paragraph>
